SQL - Structured Query Language
	- DML - Data Manipulation Language - 
		  - Insert, Update, Delete
	- DDL - Data Defination Language
		  - Create, Alter  
	- DQL - Data Query Language
		  - Select 
	- TCL - Transaction Control Language
		  - Commit, Rollback,Savepoint
	 	
Constrains
	- Primary Key - not allows null, index created implicitely
	- Foreign Key - Connect 2 tables
	- Unique Key - allows only one null, index are not created
	- Check - to add restrictions
	- Not Null - Null not allowed
	
Database Objects
	- Table
	- Index
	- View
	- Sequence
	- Synonym
	
Data Types
	- Integer
	- Varchar
	- Decimal
	- Date
	- Boolean
	- Timestamp

	
Difference between delete and truncate is that truncate can not be rolled back but the delete can.

	
Scenario:
	Online Shopping (Schema)
	- Product - [code,description,price,stock,availability]
	- Customer - [cid,cname,email,address,phone,password,status]
	- Order - [id,amount,date,cid]
	- Payment - [pid,id,mode,amount,date]
	- Ordered_Product - [code,id,qty]
	
	
